    "Let me analyze the mapped transformation to identify the reaction center.\n\nReactants: CCC(C#N)[C:20](=[N-:10])[O:21][P:22](Cl)(Cl)Cl.Cl\n\nProducts: CCC(C#N)[C:20]#[N:10].[O:21]=[P-:22](Cl)(Cl)Cl.Cl\n\nLet me trace the mapped atoms:\n\nAtom 20 (C): In reactants, bonded to =N-:10 and -O:21. In products, bonded to #N:10 (triple bond). So C20 changed from C=N to C≡N.\n\nAtom 10 (N): In reactants, =N- (double bond to C20, negative charge). In products, #N (triple bond to C20, neutral). So N10 changed from =N- to #N.\n\nAtom 21 (O): In reactants, bonded to C20 and P22. In products, double bonded to P22 (=P-). So O21 changed from -O- (bridging C20 and P22) to =O (double bond to P22 only).\n\nAtom 22 (P): In reactants, bonded to O21 and three Cl atoms. In products, bonded to =O21 and three Cl atoms, with negative charge (P-). So P22 changed from P(III) to P(V) with a double bond to O21.\n\nThe key changes:\n1. C20-N10: double bond → triple bond\n2. C20-O21: single bond → broken (no bond)\n3. O21-P22: single bond → double bond\n4. N10: negative charge → neutral\n5. P22: neutral → negative charge\n\nSo the reaction center involves:\n- Bond break: C20-O21\n- Bond change: C20=N10 → C20#N10 (double to triple)\n- Bond change: O21-P22 → O21=P22 (single to double)\n- Charge transfer: N10(-) → N10, P22 → P22(-)\n\nThis is essentially a fragmentation where the C-O bond breaks, the nitrogen forms a triple bond with carbon (losing its negative charge), and the oxygen forms a double bond with phosphorus (which gains the negative charge).\n\nThe reaction center is: C20-O21 bond cleavage, C20=N10→C20#N10, O21-P22→O21=P22, with charge migration from N10 to P22."
